<dl id="n54126a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54126a">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54126a"> 126(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Mr Dean <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54126a"><li>FW 248.26f </li><li><a href="../../flex/kf/lexkf.htm#n54126a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kf/l39kf.htm#n54126a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54126a">MS BL 47477-290</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:431 <a name="kad9" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kfd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kf/kfd8.htm#n54126a">Draft: II.1&sect;6.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&lsquo;Pray Mrs. Pilkington tell me your faults.&rsquo; &lsquo;Indeed, Sir, I must beg to be excused, for, if I can help it, you shall never find them out.&rsquo; &lsquo;No,&rsquo; says he, &lsquo;then Mr. Pilkington shall tell me.&rsquo; &lsquo;I will, Sir,&rsquo; says he, &lsquo;when I have discovered them.&rsquo; &lsquo;Pray <mark>Mr. Dean</mark>,&rsquo; says Dr. Delany, &lsquo;why will you be so unpolite, as to suppose Mrs. Pilkington has any faults?&rsquo; &lsquo;Why, I will tell you&rsquo;, replied the Dean; &lsquo;whenever I see a number of agreeable qualities in any person, I am always sure they have bad ones sufficient to poise the scale.&rsquo; I bowed, and told the Dean: &lsquo;He did me great honour.&rsquo; And in this I copied Bishop Berkley, whom I have frequently heard declare: &lsquo;That when any speech was made to him, which might be construed either into a compliment, or an affront, or, that (to make use of his own word) had two handles, he was so meek and so mild that he always took hold of the best.&rsquo; <small> Letitia Pilkington, <a name="MMLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MMLP"><cite title="source">Memoirs</cite></a> (1928) 52</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n54a02r" href="n54all.htm#n54a02r">N54 (VI.B.45):a02(r)</a>. The Dean = Jonathan Swift. </mm> </dd></dl>
